    {
        "content": "<p>tolumide-ng requested <a href=\"https://github.com/alexcrichton\">alexcrichton</a> for a review on <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12805\">PR #12805</a>.</p>",
        "id": 581093879,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1774267772
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12805#discussion_r3010245134\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>We generally prefer to avoid having conditionally-noop functions like this, so this'll want some different treatment to handle the GC feature being disabled. The general shape of things is:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Rust-defined functions are entirely <code>#[cfg]</code>'d away, aka there's a <code>#[cfg]</code> on the method itself (or the containing module if applicable)</li>\n<li>The C header needs a <code>#ifdef</code> guard to see if <code>WASMTIME_FEATURE_GC</code> is enabled.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>That way when the <code>gc</code> feature is disabled the functions \"disappear\" as opposed to being present but not actually doing anything (which can be confusing). Would you be up for refactoring in that style?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 582582058,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1774881799
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12805#discussion_r3010257370\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This is an example file where when <code>gc</code> is disabled the entire module may wish to disappear vs having lots of <code>#[cfg]</code> internally.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 582582059,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1774881799
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12805#discussion_r3010274818\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I feel it would be best to avoid the duplication here (and in a number of locations). Handling this will be a bit tricky though due to <code>to_val</code> wanting a <code>RootScope</code>. Thinking a bit about this, I think a way to thread this needle would be:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Conditionally define <code>to_val</code> based on the <code>gc</code> feature -- if it's enabled it's as-is, and if it's disabled the argument is just <code>impl AsContextMut</code> (e.g. drop the <code>RootScope</code>)</li>\n<li>For methods using <code>to_val</code> use the pattern <code>#[cfg(feature = \"gc\")] let mut store = RootScope::new(&amp;mut store);</code> -- that way it shadows the <code>store</code> local variable meaning that <code>to_val</code> works both with/without the <code>gc</code> feature.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>how's that sound?</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 582582060,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1774881800
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>alexcrichton submitted <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12805#pullrequestreview-4031086645\">PR review</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Returning now from vacation, thanks for your patience @tolumide-ng. Also I'll apologize that the scope of this issue is broadening to be a bit larger than I had originally anticipated. I thought there would be some minor edits required to get the c-api building without GC, but there's a number of API design decisions to make here which affect how exactly this works. I'm happy to help guide through these, but if you feel this is getting too broad in scope that's also totally fine.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 582582061,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1774881800
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>tolumide-ng <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12805#issuecomment-4165723158\">commented</a> on <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/12805\">PR #12805</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Returning now from vacation, thanks for your patience @tolumide-ng. Also I'll apologize that the scope of this issue is broadening to be a bit larger than I had originally anticipated. I thought there would be some minor edits required to get the c-api building without GC, but there's a number of API design decisions to make here which affect how exactly this works. I'm happy to help guide through these, but if you feel this is getting too broad in scope that's also totally fine.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Welcome back from your holiday @alexcrichton, and thank you for the review.<br>\nI'm happy to continue with the expanded scope. It looks like an informative introduction to the codebase.<br>\nI'd definitely appreciate your guidance as questions come up.</p>\n</blockquote>",
